Investigate Ford Bike Sharing Data of June 2019¶

by Dominik Marquardt¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Ford GoBike is a regional public bicycle sharing system in the San Francisco Bay Area, California. Starting in August 2013 as Bay Area Bike Share, the Ford GoBike system currently has over 2,600 bicycles in 262 stations across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose. Since 2017 the sharing service has partnered with Ford Motor Company and is now called Ford Go Bike.

Ford GoBike offers bikes that are locked into a network of docking stations across the city. The customer can unlock the bikes and lock them somewhere else. This make it perfect for one-way trips. Therer are plentz of ways people use the bikes. To get to appointments or social engagements or to get to the train. This mobility concepts is very convenient and affordable way for people of all ages.

The bikes are available for use 24 hours/day, 7 days/week, 365 days/year and riders have access to all bikes in the network when they become a member or purchase a pass.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

We investigating data from Summer of June 2019 During this time the data shows approximately 189069 bike rides in the San Francisco Bay area of California

The column header descriptions are as follows:¶

  • Trip Duration (seconds)
  • Start Time and Date
  • End Time and Date
  • Start Station ID
  • Start Station Name
  • Start Station Latitude
  • Start Station Longitude
  • End Station ID
  • End Station Name
  • End Station Latitude
  • End Station Longitude
  • Bike ID
  • User Type (Subscriber or Customer – “Subscriber” = Member or “Customer” = Casual)
Following columns are added manually¶
  • Start Time Month
  • Start Time Month Number
  • Start Time Day of the Week
  • Start Time Hour
  • Duration in minutes

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features:¶

  • data related to the start and end of a ride ** It's good for demand analysis - high or low demand.
  • User type data and timing data - whether they are a paying member or a casual user. Which day of the week bikes should be most available. This information can be used to make business decisions
  • What days are the most frequent ones for what user type

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • user_type
  • usgae duration [min]
  • start_time_weekday
  • start_time_hour
  • bike_ID

# Chaeck the usage per week day using the "start_time_weekday" feature
# Weekday usage of the Ford Go bike system
# create some helper data 
weekdays = ['Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat', 'Sun']
# actual plot
ax = sb.catplot(data=df_cleaned, x='start_time_weekday', kind='count', color = no_color, order = weekdays)
# polish the plot a bit 
ax.fig.suptitle('Bike Usage by Weekday', y=1.04, fontsize=18, fontweight='normal');
ax.set_axis_labels('Weekdays', 'Count Trips')
ax.set_xticklabels(rotation=0);

Observation Tuesdays and Wednesdays seem to be the most popular days for using the bike sharing system in June 2019. Nevertheless Mondays, Thursdays, and Fridays don't differ much. We can see a significant drop on Saturdays and Sundays by more then 10000 rides in compare to the Tuesday.This somehow gives an indicator that the Fors bike sharing is used primarily for commuting purposes during working days and less for pleasure on free days like the weekend.

The point plot shows an interesting differencde between the two groups of user types. They use the system almost in a complete invers way. Customers show a quite low usage of the bike share system during weekdays and a bit more on weekends. Subscribers are the opposite - they show high usage on weekdays and a sharp decline on the weekends for the month of June 2019.

# Create General Figure size for better visualization 
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize = (15, 10), dpi=300)
fig.suptitle('Hourly Usage - Weekdays Relation to User Type',y=1.02, horizontalalignment='right')

# Create first subplot for the customer relation to hour and weekday 
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)

#create customer data only 
customer_data = df_cleaned_filtered_30_min_duration.query('user_type == "Customer"')
customer_counts = customer_data.groupby(['start_time_weekday', 'start_time_hour']).size()
customer_counts = customer_counts.reset_index(name='count')
customer_counts = customer_counts.pivot(index='start_time_weekday', columns='start_time_hour', values='count')
# Call for the heat map plot for cutomer 
sb.heatmap(customer_counts, cmap='Blues_r');
# polish the plot for better readability
plt.title('Customer', loc='left',fontsize = 12);
# Remove labels
plt.ylabel('')    
plt.xlabel('')

# Doin principle the same for the Subscriber as we have done above 
plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
# Prepare subscriber data 
subscribers_data = df_cleaned_filtered_30_min_duration.query('user_type == "Subscriber"')
subscribers_counts = subscribers_data.groupby(['start_time_weekday', 'start_time_hour']).size()
subscribers_counts = subscribers_counts.reset_index(name='count')
subscribers_counts = subscribers_counts.pivot(index='start_time_weekday', columns='start_time_hour', values='count')
# Call heatmap plot
sb.heatmap(subscribers_counts, cmap='Blues_r');
#Polish
plt.title('Subscriber', loc='left',fontsize = 12);
plt.xlabel('Hour',y=1.04, fontsize=14, fontweight='normal');
plt.ylabel('Weekday', y=1.04, fontsize=14, fontweight='normal');
# Auto allign
fig.tight_layout()

This heat map makes the differece between the two types very intuitive obvious at a glance. It is impressive how clear and stright the subscriber show up with white strikes at 7-8am and 5-6pm.That's the commute time. Additionally one can see the clear drop in usage at saturday and sundays across all 24 hours for the subscriber. While there is also a higher usage between 7-8am and 5-6pm for weekdays for customer, we can clearly see the high increase of usage between 10am-4pm on weekdays.

Overall this plot is the best plot for getting a fast and clear insight on this two groups in relation to the most important features like weekdays and hours. I would make this plot the most important plot for my sharing system evaluation and for decision making.
